{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a7836a85-2b69-45c4-979d-ee1bb1b80678","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool` on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- These make it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key steps\n\n1. **`PackAsTool = true`** — this is the critical property that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command name users will invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **Pack it:** `dotnet pack -c Release`\n4. **Publish it:** `dotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg --api-key YOUR_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json`\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThe only truly essential additions to a normal console app are **`PackAsTool`** and **`ToolCommandName`**. Everything else is standard NuGet packaging metadata.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7083e0a7-5da5-4a73-b62f-d8873843fa65","outputTokens":466,"requestId":"CBC3:34F832:180FE1B:1B56D70:69FE899D"},"id":"b9d05c43-3da0-4a3f-92ed-261845dc147c","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:11:02.246Z","parentId":"77ba0850-219c-4170-9af7-16409778aea2"}
